From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sat, 20 Jun 2026 03:11:49 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] find: read -files0-from - from logical stdin, not the process
 fd 0
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

`parse_files0_args` slurped `std::io::stdin()` directly for
`-files0-from -`. In-process that is the ENGINE's real fd 0 (the control
channel, a parent pipe, another box's stream) — so `find -files0-from -`
both read the wrong paths AND consumed bytes from whatever owns that fd,
corrupting its stream. This is the same process-global-I/O hazard the
rest of the port eliminates; it must not be left in.

Fix: add `Dependencies::get_input() -> &RefCell<dyn Read>` (parallel to
get_output/get_error_output) and thread the reader down the parse path:
parse_args -> build_top_level_matcher_with_input -> build_matcher_tree
-> parse_files0_args, which now reads from it instead of std::io::stdin.
build_top_level_matcher keeps its old signature as a thin wrapper passing
the process stdin, so its ~58 (test) callers are untouched.

The engine's BrushFindDeps returns the shell's logical stdin from
get_input (the same reader -ok's confirm already uses). StandardDependencies
reads real stdin (standalone behavior unchanged); FakeDependencies gains a
settable input buffer plus get_error_output_as_string for assertions.

Verified: find's unit suite 212/212 (incl. two new positive tests proving
diagnostics route to the error sink and -files0-from - reads the injected
input, not process stdin); static musl build clean; and in a box,
`printf 'Cargo.toml\0src\0' | find -files0-from - -maxdepth 0` prints the
piped paths (logical stdin), not whatever sits on the engine's fd 0.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01B5MwFcipu6iwqtMPPwFhXd
